# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: annual-review-of-microbiology
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/abstract-summary] An **abstract** is a brief summary of a research article, thesis, review, conference proceeding, or any in-depth analysis of a particular subject and is often used to help the reader quickly ascertain the paper's purpose.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/abstract-summary] When used, an abstract always appears at the beginning of a manuscript or typescript, acting as the point-of-entry for any given academic paper or patent application.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/abstract-summary] Abstracting and indexing services for various academic disciplines are aimed at compiling a body of literature for that particular subject.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/abstract-summary] The terms ***précis*** or ***synopsis*** are used in some publications to refer to the same thing that other publications might call an "abstract".
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/abstract-summary] In management reports, an *executive summary* usually contains more information (and often more sensitive information) than the abstract does.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/abstract-summary] Academic literature uses the abstract to succinctly communicate complex research.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/abstract-summary] An abstract may act as a stand-alone entity instead of a full paper.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/abstract-summary] As such, an abstract is used by many organizations as the basis for selecting research that is proposed for presentation in the form of a poster, platform/oral presentation or workshop presentation at an academic conference.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/abstract-summary] Most bibliographic databases only index abstracts rather than providing the entire text of the paper.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/abstract-summary] Full texts of scientific papers must often be purchased because of copyright and/or publisher fees and therefore the abstract is a significant selling point for the reprint or electronic form of the full text.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/abstract-summary] The abstract can convey the main results and conclusions of a scientific article but the full text article must be consulted for details of the methodology, the full experimental results, and a critical discussion of the interpretations and conclusions.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/abstract-summary] Abstracts are occasionally inconsistent with full reports.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/abstract-summary] This has the potential to mislead clinicians who rely solely on the information present in the abstract without consulting the full report.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/abstract-summary] An abstract allows one to sift through copious numbers of papers for ones in which the researcher can have more confidence that they will be relevant to their research.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/abstract-summary] Once papers are chosen based on the abstract, they must be read carefully to be evaluated for relevance.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/abstract-summary] It is generally agreed that one must not base reference citations on the abstract alone, but the content of an entire paper.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/abstract-summary] This is because abstracts may not be fully representative of the full report or article.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/abstract-summary] Therefore, basing reference citations solely on the information present in the abstract could be misleading.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/abstract-summary] According to the results of a study published in *PLOS Medicine*, the "exaggerated and inappropriate coverage of research findings in the news media" is ultimately related to inaccurately reporting or over-interpreting research results in many abstract conclusions.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/abstract-summary] The history of abstracting dates back to the point when it was felt necessary to summarise the content of documents in order to make the information contained in them more accessible.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/abstract-summary] In Mesopotamia during the early second millennium BCE, clay envelopes designed to protect enclosed cuneiform documents from tampering were inscribed either with the full text of the document or a summary.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/abstract-summary] In the Greco-Roman world, many texts were abstracted: summaries of non-fiction works were known as epitomes, and in many cases the only information about works which have not survived to modernity comes from their epitomes which have survived.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/abstract-summary] Similarly, the text of many ancient Greek and Roman plays commenced with a hypothesis which summed up the play's plot.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/abstract-summary] Non-literary documents were also abstracted: the Tebtunis papyri found in the Ancient Egyptian town of Tebtunis contain abstracts of legal documents.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/abstract-summary] During the Middle Ages, the pages of scholarly texts contained summaries of their contents as marginalia, as did some manuscripts of the Code of Justinian.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/abstract-summary] The use of abstracts to summarise science originates in the early 1800s, when the secretary of the Royal Society would record brief summaries of talks into the minutes of each meeting, which were referred to as 'abstracts'.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/abstract-summary] The Royal Society abstracts from 1800 – 1837 were later collated and published in the society's journal *Philosophical Transactions*, with the first group appearing in 1832.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/abstract-summary] These abstracts were generally one or more pages long.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/abstract-summary] Other learned societies adopted similar practices.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/abstract-summary] The RAS abstracts were between one and three paragraphs long.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/abstract-summary] In both cases, these early abstracts were written by the learned society, not the author of the paper.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/abstract-summary] Perhaps the earliest example of an abstract published alongside the paper it summarises was the 1919 paper *On the Irregularities of Motion of the Foucault Pendulum* published in the *Physical Review* of the American Physical Society, which often published abstracts thereafter.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/abstract-summary] Abstracts in the United States are protected under copyright law just as any other form of written speech is protected.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/abstract-summary] Abstract is often expected to tell a complete story of the paper, as for most readers, abstract is the only part of the paper that will be read.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/abstract-summary] It should allow the reader to give an elevator pitch of the full paper.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/abstract-summary] It may also contain brief references, although some publications' standard style omits references from the abstract, reserving them for the article body (which, by definition, treats the same topics but in more depth).
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/abstract-summary] Abstract length varies by discipline and publisher requirements.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/abstract-summary] Typical length ranges from 100 to 500 words, but very rarely more than a page and occasionally just a few words.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/abstract-summary] An abstract may or may not have the section title of "abstract" explicitly listed as an antecedent to content.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/abstract-summary] Sometimes, abstracts are sectioned logically as an overview of what appears in the paper, with any of the following subheadings: Background, Introduction, Objectives, Methods, Results, Discussion, Conclusions.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/abstract-summary] Abstracts in which these subheadings are explicitly given are often called **structured abstracts**.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/abstract-summary] Abstracts that comprise one paragraph (no explicit subheadings) are often called **unstructured abstracts**.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/abstract-summary] Abstracts are important enough that IMRAD is even sometimes recast as AIMRAD.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/abstract-summary] The **informative abstract**, also known as the **complete abstract**, is a compendious summary of a paper's substance and its background, purpose, methodology, results, and conclusion.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/abstract-summary] Usually between 100 and 200 words, the informative abstract summarizes the paper's structure, its major topics and key points.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/abstract-summary] A format for scientific short reports that is similar to an informative abstract has been proposed in recent years.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/abstract-summary] Informative abstracts may be viewed as standalone documents.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/abstract-summary] The **descriptive abstract**, also known as the **limited abstract** or the **indicative abstract**, provides a description of what the paper covers without delving into its substance.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/abstract-summary] A descriptive abstract is akin to a table of contents in paragraph form.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/abstract-summary] During the late 2000s, due to the influence of computer storage and retrieval systems such as the Internet, some scientific publications, primarily those published by Elsevier, started including graphical abstracts alongside the text abstracts.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/abstract-summary] The graphic is intended to summarize or be an exemplar for the main thrust of the article.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/abstract-summary] It is not intended to be as exhaustive a summary as the text abstract, rather it is supposed to indicate the type, scope, and technical coverage of the article at a glance.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/abstract-summary] The use of graphical abstracts has been generally well received by the scientific community.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/abstract-summary] Moreover, some journals also include video abstracts and animated abstracts made by the authors to easily explain their papers.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/abstract-summary] Various methods can be used to evaluate abstract quality, e.g. rating by readers, checklists, and readability measures (such as Flesch Reading Ease).
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-analytical-chemistry] The ***Annual Review of Analytical Chemistry*** is a peer-reviewed academic journal that publishes an annual volume of review articles relevant to analytical chemistry.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-analytical-chemistry] It was established in 2008 and is published by Annual Reviews.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-analytical-chemistry] As of 2023, it is being published as open access, under the Subscribe to Open model.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-analytical-chemistry] The *Annual Review of Analytical Chemistry* was first published in 2008 by nonprofit publisher Annual Reviews.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-analytical-chemistry] Though it began with a physical edition, it is now only published electronically.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-analytical-chemistry] The *Annual Review of Analytical Chemistry* defines its scope as covering significant developments in analytical chemistry, drawing from the related disciplines of biology, engineering, and physics.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-analytical-chemistry] As of 2025, *Journal Citation Reports* lists the journal's impact factor as 7.5, ranking it eighth of 111 journals in the category "Chemistry, Analytical" and second of 44 in "Spectroscopy".
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-analytical-chemistry] It is abstracted and indexed in Scopus, Science Citation Index Expanded, EMBASE, MEDLINE, and Academic Search, among others.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-analytical-chemistry] The *Annual Review of Analytical Chemistry* is helmed by the editor or the co-editors.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-analytical-chemistry] The editor is assisted by the editorial committee, which includes associate editors, regular members, and occasionally guest editors.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-analytical-chemistry] Guest members participate at the invitation of the editor, and serve terms of one year.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-analytical-chemistry] All other members of the editorial committee are appointed by the Annual Reviews board of directors and serve five-year terms.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-analytical-chemistry] The editorial committee determines which topics should be included in each volume and solicits reviews from qualified authors.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-analytical-chemistry] Unsolicited manuscripts are not accepted.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-analytical-chemistry] Peer review of accepted manuscripts is undertaken by the editorial committee.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-analytical-chemistry] Dates indicate publication years in which someone was credited as a lead editor or co-editor of a journal volume.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-analytical-chemistry] The planning process for a volume begins well before the volume appears, so appointment to the position of lead editor generally occurred prior to the first year shown here.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-analytical-chemistry] An editor who has retired or died may be credited as a lead editor of a volume that they helped to plan, even if it is published after their retirement or death.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-analytical-chemistry] Previous members (as of 2022) were: Patrick R.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-animal-biosciences] The ***Annual Review of Animal Biosciences*** is a peer-reviewed scientific journal published by Annual Reviews.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-animal-biosciences] It releases an annual volume of review articles relevant to the fields of zoology, veterinary medicine, animal husbandry, and conservation biology.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-animal-biosciences] As of 2023, *Annual Review of Animal Biosciences* is being published as open access, under the Subscribe to Open model.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-animal-biosciences] As of 2025, *Journal Citation Reports* lists the journal's impact factor for 2024 as 8.7.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-animal-biosciences] It was rated number one of 181 titles in Zoology, number one of 86 in "Agriculture, Dairy, and Animal Sciences", number one of 170 in "Veterinary Science" and number thirteen of 177 titles in Biotechnology and Applied Microbiology.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-animal-biosciences] The *Annual Review of Animal Biosciences* was first published in 2013, with Harris A.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-animal-biosciences] Michael Roberts as the founding co-editors.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-animal-biosciences] Though it was initially published in print, as of 2021 it is only published electronically.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-animal-biosciences] The *Annual Review of Animal Biosciences* defines its scope as covering significant developments relevant to biotechnology, genomics, genetics, veterinary medicine, animal breeding, and conservation biology.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-animal-biosciences] The intended audience for the journal is scientists and veterinarians involved with wild and domestic animals.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-animal-biosciences] It is abstracted and indexed in Scopus, Science Citation Index Expanded, MEDLINE, and Embase, among others.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-anthropology] The ***Annual Review of Anthropology*** is an academic journal that publishes review articles of significant developments in anthropology and its subfields.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-anthropology] First published by Stanford University Press in 1959 under the name the *Biennial Review of Anthropology*, it became known as the current title in 1972 when its publication was assumed by Annual Reviews.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-anthropology] Strier have been the editors since 2013.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-anthropology] As of 2025, according to *Journal Citation Reports*, the journal has an impact factor of 2.7 for the year 2024.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-anthropology] In the late 1950s, anthropologist Bernard J.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-anthropology] Siegel received a grant from the National Science Foundation to establish an anthropology journal that published review articles surveying recent developments in the field.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-anthropology] Stanford University Press published the first volume *Biennial Review of Anthropology* in 1959.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-anthropology] By the publication of the third volume of the journal Siegel was approached by psychologist Ernest R.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-anthropology] Hilgard, member of the board of directors of Annual Reviews, about publishing the journal with them instead of Stanford University Press.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-anthropology] Siegel was initially resistant, though eventually saw the advantages of switching publishers.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-anthropology] The *Biennial Review of Anthropology* released seven volumes in total through 1971.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-anthropology] Beginning in 1972, the project was assumed by the nonprofit publisher Annual Reviews, with Siegel remaining as editor.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-anthropology] The format changed to annual publication instead of every other year, with the title changed to *Annual Review of Anthropology*.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-anthropology] It became the second journal title in the social sciences published by Annual Reviews, after the *Annual Review of Psychology* was first released in 1950.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-anthropology] Starting with the second volume, it included prefatory chapters where prominent anthropologists reflected on their careers.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-anthropology] The twenty-fifth volume, published in 1996, marked the first time that the journal was published electronically.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-anthropology] It defines its scope as covering significant developments in the field of anthropology; it covers subfields like archaeology, biological anthropology, linguistics, international and regional anthropology, and sociocultural anthropology.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-anthropology] As of 2024, according to *Journal Citation Reports*, the journal has an impact factor of 2.7, ranking it ninth out of 141 journals in the category "Anthropology".
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-anthropology] It is abstracted and indexed in Scopus, Science Citation Index Expanded, Social Sciences Citation Index, IBZ Online, Anthropological Literature, and Academic Search, among others.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-anthropology] The *Annual Review of Anthropology* is helmed by the editor or the co-editors.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-astronomy-and-astrophysics] The ***Annual Review of Astronomy and Astrophysics*** is an annual peer-reviewed scientific journal published by Annual Reviews.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-astronomy-and-astrophysics] The co-editors are Ewine van Dishoeck and Robert C.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-astronomy-and-astrophysics] The journal reviews scientific literature pertaining to local and distant celestial entities throughout the observable universe, as well as cosmology, instrumentation, techniques, and the history of developments.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-astronomy-and-astrophysics] As of 2025, *Journal Citation Reports* gives the journal an impact factor of 32.5, ranking it first out of 84 journals in the category "Astronomy and Astrophysics".
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-astronomy-and-astrophysics] In November 1960, the board of directors of the nonprofit publisher Annual Reviews began investigating the need for a new journal of review articles that covered developments in astronomy and astrophysics.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-astronomy-and-astrophysics] The board consulted an advisory group of experts, including Ronald Bracewell, Robert Jastrow, Joseph Kaplan, Paul Merrill, Otto Struve, and Harold Urey.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-astronomy-and-astrophysics] The editorial committee met in August 1961 to determine the authors and topics for the first volume, which was published in 1963.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-astronomy-and-astrophysics] As of 2020, it was published both in print and electronically.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-astronomy-and-astrophysics] It is abstracted and indexed in Scopus, Science Citation Index Expanded, Civil Engineering Abstracts, Inspec, and Academic Search, among others.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-astronomy-and-astrophysics] The *Annual Review of Astronomy and Astrophysics* is led by the editor or co-editors.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-astronomy-and-astrophysics] They are is assisted by the editorial committee, which includes associate editors, regular members, and occasionally guest editors.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-astronomy-and-astrophysics] Previous members (as of 2022) include: Joss Bland-Hawthorn and Eliot Quataert.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-biochemistry] The *Annual Review of Biochemistry* was the creation of Stanford University chemist and professor J.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-biochemistry] In 1930, Luck offered a course on current research in biochemistry to graduate students.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-biochemistry] In designing the course, he said he felt "knee-deep in trouble", as he believed he was sufficiently knowledgeable in only a few areas of biochemistry.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-biochemistry] He considered the volume of research to be overwhelming; there were 6,500 abstracts regarding biochemistry published in *Chemical Abstracts* that year.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-biochemistry] Luck asked about 50 biochemists in the US, United Kingdom, and Canada if an annual volume of critical reviews on biochemistry research would be useful, to which he received positive responses.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-biochemistry] This correspondence provided possible authors and topics for his first several volumes.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-biochemistry] Stanford University Press agreed to publish the journal on a three-year contract, with financial assistance from the Chemical Foundation.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-biochemistry] Stanford University gave the journal rent-free office space in 1931 for editorial and business operations.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-biochemistry] Prior to this, Luck's only experience in the publishing industry was working for a summer as a book salesman in Western Canada.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-biochemistry] Volume 1 was published in July 1932, consisting of 30 reviews from 35 authors of nine countries; the volume was 724 pages.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-biochemistry] Luck was the founding editor of the *Annual Review of Biochemistry* and held the editorship for thirty-five years.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-biochemistry] At the completion of the contract with Stanford University Press, the advisory committee of the journal, which included Carl L.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-biochemistry] Schmidt, decided to assume a legal identity as the journal's publisher, though keeping Stanford University Press as the printer.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-biochemistry] On December 12, 1934, they submitted articles of incorporation with the California Secretary of State to create Annual Review of Biochemistry, Ltd., which was organized as a nonprofit.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-biochemistry] In February 1938, the name was changed to Annual Reviews, Inc.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-biochemistry] Prior to World War II, about half of all review articles published each volume were from authors outside the US.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-biochemistry] The war caused international scientific communication to drop off dramatically, with international authorship at 25% in 1947.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-biochemistry] The breadth of material within each volume lessened when Annual Reviews added new titles in physiology and plant physiology.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-biochemistry] The *Annual Review of Biochemistry* is helmed by the editor.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-biochemistry] Guest members participate at the invitation of the editor and serve terms of one year.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-biomedical-data-science] The ***Annual Review of Biomedical Data Science*** is an academic journal published by Annual Reviews.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-biomedical-data-science] In publication since 2018, this journal covers significant developments in the field of health informatics and biomedical data science with an annual volume of review articles.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-biomedical-data-science] As of 2025, *Journal Citation Reports* lists the journal's impact factor as 6.0, ranking it seventh out of 67 journals.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-biomedical-data-science] The *Annual Review of Biomedical Data Science* was first published in 2018 by the nonprofit publisher Annual Reviews.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-biomedical-data-science] The journal focuses on biomedical data science, the development of scientific methods to acquire, annotate, organize, analyze, and interpret biomedical data and extract knowledge about life, health, and disease.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-biomedical-data-science] The *Annual Review of Biomedical Data Science* is abstracted and indexed in Science Citation Index Expanded, Scopus and BIOSIS Previews, among others.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-biomedical-data-science] The *Annual Review of Biomedical Data Science* is helmed by the editor or the co-editors.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-microbiology] The ***Annual Review of Microbiology*** is a peer-reviewed academic journal that publishes review articles about microbiology.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-microbiology] It was first published in 1947 as the third journal title released by Annual Reviews.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-microbiology] It covers significant developments in the field of microbiology, including the study of bacteria, archaea, viruses, and unicellular eukaryotes.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-microbiology] As of 2020, it has had four editors, with Charles E.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-microbiology] Nicholas Ornston serving more than twenty years each.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-microbiology] The *Annual Review of Microbiology* was first published in 1947, the third journal title released by the publishing company Annual Reviews, following titles in biochemistry and physiology.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-microbiology] From 1956 to 1958, Pierre Grabar provided a summary of the microbiologic literature appearing in the Russian language through a partnership with the National Science Foundation.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-microbiology] This was no longer necessary as abstracts became increasingly common, as well as translations from Russian to English.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-microbiology] From 1986 onward, the journal placed more of an emphasis on parasites.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-microbiology] It defines its scope as microbiology, including bacteria, archaea, viruses, and unicellular eukaryotes.
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-microbiology] As of 2025, *Journal Citation Reports* lists the journal's 2024 impact factor as 9.9, ranking it twelfth of 163 journal titles in the category "Microbiology".
[src:annual-review-of-microbiology/annual-review-of-microbiology] The *Annual Review of Microbiology* is helmed by the editor.
